response:
 When we roll a fair 6-sided die, there are 6 possible outcomes. When we roll four fair 6-sided dice, there are 6^4 = 1296 possible outcomes. For the four dice to all show the same number, there are only 6 possible outcomes (one for each number on the die). Therefore, the number of outcomes where not all four dice show the same number is 1296 - 6 = 1290. The probability that when we roll four fair 6-sided dice, they won't all show the same number is \frac{1290}{1296} = \frac{215}{216}.
</think> <answer> \frac{215}{216}
</answer>

